{{Unreferenced|date=June 2007}} [[File:Seal of the United States Virgin Islands.svg|right|200px]]
The new '''seal of the [[United States Virgin Islands]]''' features the three-island design of the main islands of [[Saint Croix, U.S. Virgin Islands|Saint Croix]], [[Saint John, U.S. Virgin Islands|Saint John]] and [[Saint Thomas, U.S. Virgin Islands|Saint Thomas]], often seen throughout the territory. It reads "Government of the United States Virgin Islands". It replaces{{when|date=October 2013}} an earlier seal similar to the [[flag of the United States Virgin Islands]], which was based on the central design of the [[Great Seal of the United States]]. The seal also contains the [[flag of the United States]] and also the [[flag of Denmark]] to symbolize its former status as a [[Danish West Indies|Danish colony]] before 1917. There's also, centered in the seal, a [[bananaquit]], the island's [[national bird]]
Designed by St. Thomas artist Mitchlyn E. Davis, Sr. {{cn|date=November 2017}}
